      "id": "diagnostic",
      "type": "diagnostic",
      "uiTag": "Misconception check",
      "uiColor": "red",
      "title": "Quick question first…",
      "question": "In a series circuit with two identical bulbs, what happens to the current as it passes through the first bulb?",
      "options": [
        "Some current is used up by the first bulb, so less reaches the second",
        "The current is the same everywhere in the circuit",
        "The current doubles after each bulb",
        "The current splits equally between the two bulbs"
      ],
      "correctIndex": 1,
      "misconceptionFeedback": "⚠️ Common misconception! Current is NOT ‘used up’ by components. In a series circuit, the current is the same at every point. What gets transferred is energy, not charge. The electrons keep flowing around the whole loop.",
      "correctFeedback": "✓ Correct! In a series circuit, current is the same everywhere. Charge is conserved: electrons are not used up. Energy is transferred by each component, but the current stays constant throughout.",
      "bestSource": "BEST resource: AQA Physics specification 4.2.3: Series circuits"
    },
    {
      "id": "concept",
      "type": "concept",
      "uiTag": "Concept",
      "uiColor": "blue",
      "title": "Series Circuits",
      "svgDiagram": "series-circuit",
      "bodyHTML": "In a <strong>series circuit</strong>, components are connected <strong>one after another</strong> in a single loop. Three key rules: (1) The <strong>current is the same</strong> through every component. (2) The <strong>total p.d.</strong> of the supply is <strong>shared</strong> between the components. (3) The <strong>total resistance</strong> is the sum of the individual resistances: R<sub>total</sub> = R<sub>1</sub> + R<sub>2</sub> + …",
      "keyEquation": "R_total = R₁ + R₂ + …",
      "diagram": {
        "type": "equation-breakdown",
        "variables": [
          {
            "symbol": "I",
            "label": "Current (same everywhere)",
            "unit": "A",
            "color": "cyan"
          },
          {
            "symbol": "V",
            "label": "Voltage (shared)",
            "unit": "V",
            "color": "purple"
          },
          {
            "symbol": "R",
            "label": "Resistance (adds up)",
            "unit": "Ω",
            "color": "amber"
          }
        ],
        "relationships": [
          "I is the SAME at every point in a series circuit",
          "V_total = V₁ + V₂ + … (voltages add up)",
          "R_total = R₁ + R₂ + … (resistances add up)"
        ]
      },
      "keyWords": [
        "series",
        "current",
        "potential difference",
        "shared",
        "total resistance"
      ],
      "commonErrors": [
        "Thinking current is ‘used up’ by each component",
        "Adding voltages instead of realising they are shared from the supply",
        "Forgetting to add all resistances for total resistance"
      ]
    },
